WEBVTT

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:01.400
Cool.

00:00:01.400 --> 00:00:05.100
Okay, so for those of you not aware, North Sky

00:00:05.100 --> 00:00:05.580
is social.

00:00:05.580 --> 00:00:10.300
So we're basically a cooperative based in, actually established in

00:00:10.300 --> 00:00:12.400
BC Canada here in Vancouver.

00:00:12.480 --> 00:00:16.590
So our priority is basically really about building a community for two

00:00:16.590 --> 00:00:20.080
-spirit LGBTQI plus people and marginalized identities.

00:00:20.140 --> 00:00:22.980
I want to focus on the second, or sort of emphasis

00:00:23.280 --> 00:00:25.120
on the second, as I feel over the past year has

00:00:25.120 --> 00:00:27.890
sort of been pigeonholed into the queer community.

00:00:28.100 --> 00:00:30.990
Quite a few other things, like I myself, you know

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:32.670
, I'm actually Sudanese-American.

00:00:32.680 --> 00:00:35.100
Both of my parents are from Sudan, born and raised,

00:00:35.130 --> 00:00:39.120
actually, in America and grew up in Washington State, so

00:00:39.270 --> 00:00:41.640
like nine hours away from here.

00:00:41.640 --> 00:00:44.760
Yeah, so if you kind of look at where Blue Sky

00:00:44.760 --> 00:00:46.790
, I need to walk up front here, sorry.

00:00:46.860 --> 00:00:51.080
So kind of look at Blue Sky sort of like started sending

00:00:51.080 --> 00:00:54.540
out invites April, May 2023.

00:00:54.540 --> 00:00:56.860
Over time, you know, we kind of saw rapid growth

00:00:57.160 --> 00:00:57.290
.

00:00:57.290 --> 00:00:59.560
And so now around 45 million users.

00:00:59.560 --> 00:01:02.790
And it was actually a beginning of last year when North Sky

00:01:02.900 --> 00:01:06.610
sort of started to assemble and we kind of found established ourselves

00:01:06.610 --> 00:01:06.690
.

00:01:06.980 --> 00:01:10.090
If we look at the reason for that, there was quite

00:01:10.140 --> 00:01:12.480
a few issues that sort of happened.

00:01:12.620 --> 00:01:16.610
One of the larger incidents early on was actually when Evita

00:01:16.630 --> 00:01:19.880
, who is a basically a black community organizer, sort of

00:01:19.880 --> 00:01:22.920
discovered that you could create handles with the N-word,

00:01:22.940 --> 00:01:24.510
just easily racial slurs.

00:01:24.800 --> 00:01:28.160
And then Blue Sky did not respond to this for multiple weeks

00:01:28.160 --> 00:01:28.280
.

00:01:28.280 --> 00:01:31.130
Developers were sort of like left to bear the burden of

00:01:31.130 --> 00:01:33.900
actually communicating and kind of trying to explain what's happening.

00:01:33.900 --> 00:01:36.950
Users were really confused about what these code changes were.

00:01:36.950 --> 00:01:38.760
Were they trying to hide things, mask things?

00:01:38.760 --> 00:01:40.040
It was just sort of a big, hot mess.

00:01:40.060 --> 00:01:45.260
Later on, then actually a series of issues, the hammer

00:01:45.280 --> 00:01:47.030
incident, one user base said like, "Hey, I

00:01:47.090 --> 00:01:50.300
want to hit this person with a hammer." That resulted in

00:01:50.440 --> 00:01:53.510
introducing the feature to actually block people.

00:01:53.730 --> 00:01:56.900
And basically, throughout all of this, we also saw a

00:01:56.900 --> 00:02:00.750
lot of issues around racism, transphobia, discrimination.

00:02:00.750 --> 00:02:04.660
And actually, and so a lot of it early on was

00:02:04.960 --> 00:02:07.860
due to Blue Sky not having really TNS, trust and

00:02:07.870 --> 00:02:09.460
safety as a priority.

00:02:09.500 --> 00:02:13.770
And then we sort of saw an acceleration of these issues sort

00:02:13.770 --> 00:02:16.260
of happening as they're able to actually, I see it

00:02:16.260 --> 00:02:19.790
kind of grew their moderation services and hired more people, which

00:02:19.820 --> 00:02:23.110
in a way allowed them to actually do a better job of

00:02:23.110 --> 00:02:23.840
moderating.

00:02:23.840 --> 00:02:27.500
But because they didn't actually understand the context of minorities,

00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:30.780
they actually ended up targeting minorities as a consequence of that.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:34.980
And then we also saw the Jesse's single incident.

00:02:34.980 --> 00:02:38.030
So basically, after Trump was elected, a bunch of people

00:02:38.030 --> 00:02:40.770
moved over to a single who's basically known bad actor,

00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:44.120
started to sort of harass people and you started panicking about

00:02:44.120 --> 00:02:44.600
him.

00:02:44.620 --> 00:02:46.320
And over the course of two days, he was like,

00:02:46.360 --> 00:02:48.430
he was basically, he was suspended, unsuspended,

00:02:48.470 --> 00:02:49.800
suspended again, and unsuspended.

00:02:49.800 --> 00:02:53.630
And then basically told that, well, he's screenshotting

00:02:53.640 --> 00:02:56.180
people and sharing on Twitter, which is actually a separate platform

00:02:56.300 --> 00:02:56.370
.

00:02:56.480 --> 00:02:58.430
So we don't target that, but we've actually seen

00:02:58.460 --> 00:03:01.520
a lot of people actually suspended for doing the same things.

00:03:01.610 --> 00:03:08.490
And then just after Trump was an inauguration ceremony, every

00:03:08.690 --> 00:03:15.660
single major social media platform removed all protections for LGBT people,

00:03:15.660 --> 00:03:19.990
minorities, basically they removed them from classification as hate speech.

00:03:20.040 --> 00:03:24.480
So it kind of showed that, oh, my screen just

00:03:24.690 --> 00:03:25.630
died.

00:03:25.630 --> 00:03:27.160
Yes, let me fix that very quickly.

00:03:27.160 --> 00:03:33.000
Is it back yet?

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:33.630
There it is.

00:03:33.640 --> 00:03:34.280
Yeah.

00:03:34.300 --> 00:03:34.800
Yeah.

00:03:34.800 --> 00:03:37.530
And so it's, and so we see then actually over

00:03:37.560 --> 00:03:40.130
the past few, we saw increased targeting of, especially of

00:03:40.210 --> 00:03:42.760
transgender people during, throughout all of this.

00:03:42.760 --> 00:03:45.890
Charlie Kirk incident, everybody's familiar with that.

00:03:45.960 --> 00:03:50.100
The US basically sends a letter to every single major social media

00:03:50.100 --> 00:03:54.550
platform saying, "We expect you to handle the Charlie Kirk

00:03:54.550 --> 00:03:56.990
discourse appropriately.

00:03:57.070 --> 00:03:59.170
If you do not, we'll revoke your Section 230

00:03:59.170 --> 00:04:04.130
status." Section 230 basically says that social media platforms are common

00:04:04.140 --> 00:04:04.600
carriers.

00:04:04.600 --> 00:04:06.780
And so to revoke it, suddenly now you as a

00:04:06.780 --> 00:04:10.590
social media platform are responsible for whatever your views are saying.

00:04:10.880 --> 00:04:14.920
And so what really kind of saw is that every single time

00:04:14.920 --> 00:04:20.690
is that minorities are always discarded as soon as anything becomes difficult

00:04:20.690 --> 00:04:20.830
.

00:04:21.080 --> 00:04:24.580
And so when North Skies sort of started to assemble,

00:04:24.600 --> 00:04:26.870
we sort of actually began with sort of an idea.

00:04:26.870 --> 00:04:29.860
What does it mean if we actually had a space, you

00:04:29.860 --> 00:04:31.320
know, we can actually speak freely?

00:04:31.320 --> 00:04:36.100
What if we could like, you know, really celebrate our

00:04:36.160 --> 00:04:38.650
successes, you know, our challenges, like provide and support

00:04:38.860 --> 00:04:39.790
one another?

00:04:40.120 --> 00:04:43.100
And, you know, and not have people that, you

00:04:43.180 --> 00:04:45.790
know, shit all over it, quite simply.

00:04:46.120 --> 00:04:49.800
And so it was because I started talking about it.

00:04:49.800 --> 00:04:52.220
We kind of like had like a lot of intense discussions and

00:04:52.310 --> 00:04:54.510
it kind of came down to like it's not really about

00:04:54.520 --> 00:04:57.000
, you know, an individual.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:04:59.800
It's really about, you know, caring for the community

00:04:59.810 --> 00:05:00.600
that they can thrive in.

00:05:01.180 --> 00:05:03.420
And then as a consequence, we actually kind of like encourage

00:05:03.510 --> 00:05:06.990
these community dynamics that support those individuals sort of create like a

00:05:07.120 --> 00:05:09.720
nice like self-reinforcing positive environment where it

00:05:09.720 --> 00:05:13.480
's like you as a person contribute to the community and community

00:05:13.480 --> 00:05:16.760
return actually contributes towards your success and protection.

00:05:16.760 --> 00:05:20.760
And that was kind of where it was kind of came down

00:05:20.760 --> 00:05:23.250
to like how do we actually focus on the needs of the

00:05:23.280 --> 00:05:26.520
people sort of looking at the common needs while also sort of

00:05:26.550 --> 00:05:28.550
providing an agency at the same time?

00:05:28.590 --> 00:05:31.080
So that way sort of like we're not forcing you to

00:05:31.100 --> 00:05:33.320
abide by rules, but actually also giving you the ability to

00:05:33.320 --> 00:05:34.600
actually kind of participate in them.

00:05:34.630 --> 00:05:39.370
And really when we kind of talked about that, it was

00:05:39.370 --> 00:05:41.840
actually like, okay, then issues kind of become like,

00:05:41.840 --> 00:05:43.960
you know, within the community is like how do we actually

00:05:43.990 --> 00:05:47.560
sort of de-escalate people from like fight or

00:05:47.560 --> 00:05:52.410
flight as, you know, every single, actually every single

00:05:52.410 --> 00:05:55.730
person in North Sky social like the members and volunteers, we

00:05:55.730 --> 00:05:58.980
have all been subjected to different types of trauma, you know

00:05:59.100 --> 00:06:01.230
, whether it is like racial, sexual, gender-based

00:06:01.560 --> 00:06:01.640
.

00:06:01.640 --> 00:06:04.680
We've all actually kind of like been targeted by this.

00:06:04.800 --> 00:06:07.720
And then that kind of means that we have to kind of

00:06:07.720 --> 00:06:11.100
like create spaces that allow for decompression at the same time

00:06:11.100 --> 00:06:13.580
as when you're existing in a space, you know,

00:06:13.580 --> 00:06:15.760
whether it's online or in real life, we're constantly

00:06:15.760 --> 00:06:17.080
being targeted and harassed.

00:06:17.100 --> 00:06:19.730
There is never any point where you can actually process that in

00:06:19.730 --> 00:06:20.520
a healthy manner.

00:06:20.550 --> 00:06:25.350
And so that's kind of where when we started actually listening

00:06:25.400 --> 00:06:27.400
at like, okay, what does we actually moderate to do

00:06:27.400 --> 00:06:32.680
moderation, to church trust and safety with this context?

00:06:32.680 --> 00:06:34.500
And so that's where kind of like we're sort of

00:06:34.500 --> 00:06:37.030
justice, you know, that was really what we started writing

00:06:37.250 --> 00:06:38.140
everything out.

00:06:38.160 --> 00:06:40.410
That was like the core tenant of it.

00:06:40.610 --> 00:06:44.690
And the other part of it was actually human to human moderation

00:06:44.920 --> 00:06:48.350
where our actions aren't, you know, opaque.

00:06:48.350 --> 00:06:51.100
Like I expect to say like one of the first moderate actions

00:06:51.140 --> 00:06:54.920
that we actually took was where we started migrating people over

00:06:55.050 --> 00:06:57.190
and one user just like made a post that was actually a

00:06:57.190 --> 00:06:58.680
clear violation of our guidelines.

00:06:58.680 --> 00:07:02.050
Rather than just using Ozone to take it down, we

00:07:02.050 --> 00:07:05.070
actually notified them saying, "Hey, you've made this

00:07:05.070 --> 00:07:05.590
post.

00:07:05.640 --> 00:07:07.710
It violates the guidelines for these reasons.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:10.840
Can you please remove it?" They immediately deleted it.

00:07:12.460 --> 00:07:13.980
And that's where actually we kind of, we gave them

00:07:13.980 --> 00:07:17.050
the agency, the choice to actually participate in actually building a

00:07:17.050 --> 00:07:18.320
healthy community.

00:07:18.390 --> 00:07:21.740
And so we say, you know, it's basically like

00:07:21.740 --> 00:07:23.800
, you know, let's check in with you.

00:07:23.920 --> 00:07:26.590
Let's actually see how you're doing.

00:07:26.590 --> 00:07:30.240
And then the other part is really like our focus is really

00:07:30.240 --> 00:07:33.400
like, how do we actually handle these inter-community

00:07:33.540 --> 00:07:36.550
issues, you know, within the community itself.

00:07:36.610 --> 00:07:39.550
As in a way it's, I say it's easier

00:07:39.560 --> 00:07:43.530
to moderate the challenges actually targeting your community than it is actually

00:07:43.740 --> 00:07:44.750
moderate what's happening within it.

00:07:44.790 --> 00:07:50.120
And so when we kind of talk about those spaces, there

00:07:50.120 --> 00:07:51.400
's also the other issue sort of, you know, we

00:07:51.430 --> 00:07:55.850
say like protecting like from external influences, is we saw like

00:07:55.850 --> 00:07:58.620
on, on HE protocol in particular, is actually there's

00:07:58.640 --> 00:07:59.880
a lot of challenges come with it.

00:07:59.880 --> 00:08:02.030
Like these are two examples from earlier this year, where it

00:08:02.030 --> 00:08:04.280
's like one person was like, you know, a person

00:08:04.280 --> 00:08:06.610
took a picture of her and proceeded to use AI to dress

00:08:06.690 --> 00:08:07.630
it up differently.

00:08:07.920 --> 00:08:12.440
Another one is a political activist targeted for his activism.

00:08:12.460 --> 00:08:13.900
So he's saying, "Hey, I have to actually

00:08:13.900 --> 00:08:16.240
delete all my content because we're all being targeted by this

00:08:16.240 --> 00:08:19.960
." Let me click that again.

00:08:20.060 --> 00:08:20.340
Yeah.

00:08:20.340 --> 00:08:23.080
And then the other part is where we basically see AI tech

00:08:23.080 --> 00:08:26.430
bros who basically see this firehose where all this

00:08:26.460 --> 00:08:29.140
data is in public, I can use it for training purposes

00:08:29.140 --> 00:08:29.250
.

00:08:29.320 --> 00:08:31.640
Not commenting on your status announcement.

00:08:31.640 --> 00:08:36.120
And so, and so sort of like, you know,

00:08:36.120 --> 00:08:37.750
and when this happened, they're like, "Oh my

00:08:37.750 --> 00:08:39.450
god, this is amazing thing I just published." And everybody

00:08:39.660 --> 00:08:40.150
freaks out.

00:08:40.220 --> 00:08:45.230
Fun fact, I emailed Hugging Face's privacy group,

00:08:45.240 --> 00:08:47.620
basically asking them if they can remove her GDPR violations.

00:08:47.620 --> 00:08:48.520
I never got a response.

00:08:48.520 --> 00:08:52.200
Yeah.

00:08:52.200 --> 00:08:54.120
And so, by the way, this is an illustration my

00:08:54.120 --> 00:08:55.640
daughter made for me for this talk.

00:08:55.740 --> 00:08:57.770
She is watching this right now.

00:08:58.100 --> 00:09:03.160
Yeah.

00:09:03.160 --> 00:09:05.960
And so, really kind of like, we want to have

00:09:05.960 --> 00:09:09.880
a community space where people can actually experience joy together.

00:09:09.880 --> 00:09:13.270
You know, and actually be able to like discuss not just

00:09:13.270 --> 00:09:16.350
their challenges, but their successes, you know, they can

00:09:16.350 --> 00:09:17.100
create together.

00:09:17.160 --> 00:09:20.060
But at the same time, when you start creating these spaces

00:09:20.140 --> 00:09:23.260
, you always have people outside of it who want to invade

00:09:23.270 --> 00:09:26.010
it, who want to disrupt it, or they may not

00:09:26.010 --> 00:09:27.490
even be nefarious.

00:09:27.490 --> 00:09:30.440
I think it was what, last week, Rudy made a

00:09:30.440 --> 00:09:32.890
post where he's talking about like the hustle.

00:09:32.890 --> 00:09:36.120
And then somebody responds like, "I do not support hustle

00:09:36.140 --> 00:09:37.250
culture." And Rudy's like, "Oh, I'm

00:09:37.340 --> 00:09:37.560
sorry.

00:09:37.560 --> 00:09:42.070
I didn't code switch." It's like those types of

00:09:42.070 --> 00:09:45.070
actions where it's like, they'll blindly walk into the

00:09:45.410 --> 00:09:46.230
space.

00:09:46.280 --> 00:09:48.490
And that's kind of one of the issues that we kind

00:09:48.490 --> 00:09:52.190
of always see happening as we start kind of doing community building

00:09:52.190 --> 00:09:52.280
.

00:09:52.280 --> 00:09:55.350
And so, that's kind of where we then sort of

00:09:55.350 --> 00:09:58.350
like, kind of discussion early on was also, like,

00:09:58.350 --> 00:10:00.860
okay, then we have feeds, which are great.

00:10:00.860 --> 00:10:03.420
You know, they kind of provide for a lot of flexibility

00:10:03.480 --> 00:10:03.560
.

00:10:03.580 --> 00:10:06.200
You know, you can create a feed that has specific content

00:10:06.450 --> 00:10:06.620
.

00:10:06.620 --> 00:10:10.020
Black Sky has their community feed, as an example.

00:10:10.320 --> 00:10:12.380
North Sky, we've created our own also.

00:10:12.610 --> 00:10:15.000
But at the same time, it's sort of like,

00:10:15.020 --> 00:10:16.130
people can still access it.

00:10:16.220 --> 00:10:18.040
You know, you can kind of do some logic within it

00:10:18.040 --> 00:10:18.250
.

00:10:18.280 --> 00:10:21.860
But it doesn't really solve the public side of things.

00:10:22.040 --> 00:10:23.850
And so that's when we start, okay, how do

00:10:23.850 --> 00:10:27.190
we actually shift away from just talking about feeds towards actually creating

00:10:27.250 --> 00:10:27.520
spaces?

00:10:30.300 --> 00:10:31.340
And so it's sort of like, you know, okay

00:10:31.340 --> 00:10:32.050
, what does it look like?

00:10:32.160 --> 00:10:35.440
You know, how do users interact with these spaces?

00:10:35.450 --> 00:10:37.530
Sorry, I'm also kind of spotting because I just

00:10:37.530 --> 00:10:38.840
wrote all those two days ago.

00:10:38.860 --> 00:10:39.220
Yeah.

00:10:39.220 --> 00:10:41.100
And it's like, what are the new ways you can

00:10:41.160 --> 00:10:44.260
actually kind of create those, create interactions within these spaces?

00:10:44.380 --> 00:10:46.440
So is that sort of like breaking away from actually having a

00:10:46.460 --> 00:10:48.360
single feed to actually, okay, how do you actually have

00:10:48.360 --> 00:10:52.790
a space that has different ways of actually interacting with that space

00:10:52.790 --> 00:10:53.400
itself?

00:10:53.400 --> 00:10:58.200
And then, in what ways does it actually result in a

00:10:58.200 --> 00:10:59.640
positive environment too?

00:10:59.900 --> 00:11:04.600
And this is kind of where, I call it Stratos

00:11:04.730 --> 00:11:08.040
, sort of a private data solution.

00:11:08.060 --> 00:11:10.300
Kind of like, that's where it kind of came out

00:11:10.390 --> 00:11:11.600
of that.

00:11:11.600 --> 00:11:15.410
As when I originally wrote the proposal, there was like no

00:11:15.480 --> 00:11:16.240
announcements yet.

00:11:16.240 --> 00:11:18.600
I think it was basically like, Nick had written some things

00:11:18.600 --> 00:11:19.800
, Paul had written some things.

00:11:19.900 --> 00:11:21.370
It's all kind of very heavy theoretical.

00:11:21.580 --> 00:11:23.080
But this is where we kind of talk about, okay,

00:11:23.080 --> 00:11:25.260
let's actually do private data in a way that's actually

00:11:25.260 --> 00:11:25.960
permissioned.

00:11:27.660 --> 00:11:30.160
Where you can kind of like, allow for multiple spaces to

00:11:30.200 --> 00:11:30.680
exist.

00:11:30.680 --> 00:11:35.080
But at the same time, have some governance in there too

00:11:35.180 --> 00:11:35.240
.

00:11:35.240 --> 00:11:37.430
And that's kind of where we're saying, okay,

00:11:37.470 --> 00:11:40.070
I should actually have the ability to actually moderate this, was

00:11:40.080 --> 00:11:41.800
one of the critical aspects of it.

00:11:41.800 --> 00:11:45.720
When I published the first proposal, the, one of the

00:11:45.720 --> 00:11:49.110
common feedbacks, I was like, okay, why don

00:11:49.110 --> 00:11:50.800
't you do end-to-end encryption?

00:11:51.820 --> 00:11:53.380
I was like, okay, let me actually think about this

00:11:53.380 --> 00:11:53.390
.

00:11:53.490 --> 00:11:54.860
So I looked at the MLS spec, I read it

00:11:54.860 --> 00:11:56.880
, I talked to Ian from Pyregos.

00:11:56.880 --> 00:12:00.370
And it's quite something that doesn't, it doesn't

00:12:00.370 --> 00:12:01.450
work at that type.

00:12:01.460 --> 00:12:03.680
So like, end-to-end encryption is essentially,

00:12:03.700 --> 00:12:05.860
you know, like, I'm talking to Nick, nobody

00:12:05.870 --> 00:12:06.780
can take part in it.

00:12:06.810 --> 00:12:09.110
And then I add another person to it, another take part

00:12:09.220 --> 00:12:09.430
in it.

00:12:09.490 --> 00:12:11.480
But they don't see any of the messages from before,

00:12:11.580 --> 00:12:13.150
because it's all encrypted if it's satisfied.

00:12:13.250 --> 00:12:15.970
And so if you want to moderate it, then whoever the

00:12:16.060 --> 00:12:17.810
